 nutrition and immune challenges, can have long-lasting effects on subsequent physiological parameters. Many of these organizational effects are mediated by hormones, including corticosterone (CORT), a hormone involved in nutrient mobilization, immune response modulation, and responses to stressors. While the effects of exogenous CORT during development on later-life physiology have demonstrated the important role this hormone plays in developmental plasticity, relatively less attention has been paid to other factors capable of driving a CORT-mediated cascade of phenotypic effects. We tested the effect of nonpathogenic immune challenges during different stages of development and used levels of CORT in feathers (CORT f ) to investigate whether CORT levels during development (when the feathers were grown) could predict variation in traits at adulthood. Mallards (  Anas platyrhynchos  ) exhibit a variety of traits as adults that could be influenced by CORT, including a carotenoid-pigmented beak used in mate choice and melanin-based patterning in the speculum of the wing that has no known signaling function. We found that nonpathogenic immune challenges during development had no detectable effects on duckling CORT f , which suggests that more robust immune challenges are required to create a sustained increase in circulating CORT levels. However, duckling CORT f  predicted multiple traits at adulthood: higher levels of CORT f  were associated with increases in circulating carotenoid levels, degree of carotenoid-based beak coloration, and mass gain. We failed to demonstrate a link between melanin-based speculum patterning and CORT at time of trait development, although speculum patterning was both affected by immune challenge treatment and correlated with adult immune function. These results support the &ldquo;quality hypothesis,&rdquo; which states that variation in CORT could be positively correlated with traits reflecting individual quality under certain conditions, and also suggest that the speculum in Mallards may be able to serve as an honest signal.  Las condiciones durante el desarrollo, incluyendo la nutrici&oacute;n y los desaf&iacute;os inmunol&oacute;gicos, pueden tener efectos de larga duraci&oacute;n en par&aacute;metros fisiol&oacute;gicos subsecuentes. Muchos de estos efectos organizacionales est&aacute;n mediados por hormonas, incluyendo la corticosterona (CORT), una hormona involucrada en la movilizaci&oacute;n de nutrientes, la modulaci&oacute;n de la actividad inmune y la respuesta a agentes de estr&eacute;s. Mientras que los efectos de la exposici&oacute;n a la CORT ex&oacute;gena durante el desarrollo sobre la fisiolog&iacute;a de etapas de vida posteriores han demostrado el importante papel que cumple esta hormona en la plasticidad fenot&iacute;pica, se ha prestado relativamente poca atenci&oacute;n a otros factores capaces de producir una cascada de efectos mediados por la CORT. En este estudio evaluamos los efectos de desaf&iacute;os inmunol&oacute;gicos no patog&eacute;nicos durante diferentes etapas del desarrollo y usamos niveles de CORT en las plumas (CORT f ) para investigar si los niveles de CORT durante el desarrollo (durante el crecimiento de las plumas) podr&iacute;an predecir variaci&oacute;n de rasgos en la adultez. Los adultos de   Anas platyrhynchos   exhiben una variedad de rasgos que podr&iacute;an verse influenciados por la CORT, incluyendo un pico con pigmentos carotenoides usado en escogencia de pareja y un patr&oacute;n en el esp&eacute;culo del ala basado en melaninas de funci&oacute;n desconocida. Encontramos que los desaf&iacute;os inmunol&oacute;gicos no patog&eacute;nicos durante el desarrollo no tuvieron efectos detectables en la CORT f  de los polluelos, lo que sugiere que se requieren desaf&iacute;os inmunes m&aacute;s robustos para crear un incremento sostenido en los niveles de CORT circulante. Sin embargo, la CORT f  de los polluelos predijo m&uacute;ltiples rasgos en los adultos: mayores niveles de CORT f  se asociaron con incrementos en los niveles de carotenoides, el grado de la coloraci&oacute;n del pico basada en carotenoides y la ganancia de peso. No pudimos demostrar una relaci&oacute;n entre el patr&oacute;n basado en melanina del esp&eacute;culo y la CORT durante el desarrollo del rasgo, aunque el patr&oacute;n del esp&eacute;culo s&iacute; fue afectado por el tratamiento de desaf&iacute;o inmunol&oacute;gico y se correlacion&oacute; con la funci&oacute;n inmune de los adultos. Estos resultados apoyan la hip&oacute;tesis de calidad, que establece que la variaci&oacute;n en CORT podr&iacute;a estar positivamente correlacionada con la calidad de los individuos bajo ciertas condiciones. Los resultados tambi&eacute;n sugieren que el esp&eacute;culo en   A. platyrhynchos   podr&iacute;a servir como una se&ntilde;al honesta.   Palabras clave:  Coloraci&oacute;n estructural, coloraci&oacute;n mel&aacute;nica, condiciones durante la vida temprana, esp&eacute;culo, hormonas glucocorticoides, ornamentaci&oacute;n con carotenoides, plasticidad durante el desarrollo, se&ntilde;ales honestas.  Conditions during early life can have profound effects on the developmental trajectory of animals ( Metcalfe and Monaghan 2001 ,  Monaghan 2008 ). This phenotypic variation is frequently produced via the actions of hormones, because hormones can alter cellular or physiological processes in response to environmental information ( Nelson 2000 ,  Dufty et al. 2002 ,  Monaghan 2008 ). A diverse suite of environmental cues can be described as harmful or unpredictable perturbations (i.e. stressors), and the hormonal responses to these stressors are particularly important during development because they can exert strong organizational influences on physiology, behavior, and fitness ( Lindstr&ouml;m 1999 ,  Blas et al. 2007 ,  Spencer and MacDougall-Shackleton 2011 ). Specifically, early-life activation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, resulting in the subsequent release of glucocorticoid (GC) hormones, affects early-life energy management that can create trade-offs responsible for producing later-life phenotypic variation ( Spencer and Verhulst 2007 ,  Monaghan 2008 ,  Spencer et al. 2009 ).  The actions of GCs such as corticosterone (CORT), the primary avian GC, can be adaptive by modulating physiology and behavior to cope with stressors ( Sapolsky et al. 2000 ,  Charmandari et al. 2005 ). For example, in nestling birds, food limitation increases levels of CORT, which triggers begging behavior that increases parental provisioning ( Kitaysky et al. 2001 ,  Quillfeldt et al. 2006 ,  Loiseau et al. 2008b ). However, sustained elevated levels of CORT during development can affect metabolism, size, and cognitive ability in the short term ( Kitaysky et al. 2003 ,  Spencer and Verhulst 2007 ,  2008 ,  Loiseau et al. 2008a ,  Fairhurst et al. 2013 ,  Crino et al. 2014b ) and can also drive variation in exploration and incubation behaviors, body size, and HPA axis activation weeks to months later ( Spencer et al. 2003 ,  2009 ,  Pravosudov and Kitaysky 2006 ,  Butler et al. 2010 ,  Almasi et al. 2012a ,  Love et al. 2013 ,  Crino et al. 2014a ). Thus, responses to stressors during early life, via actions of CORT, may be adaptive in confronting a current stressor, but may also affect multiple phenotypic traits throughout development and into adulthood.  These persistent, pleiotropic effects of CORT have been recognized and put into broader frameworks ( Spencer and MacDougall-Shackleton 2011 ,  Cohen et al. 2012 ), including investigations of CORT's role in the development of sexually selected traits. The &ldquo;developmental stress hypothesis&rdquo; formalized this thinking, demonstrating that physiological responses to conditions during development can affect both the ornamentation and quality of the individual at adulthood ( Nowicki et al. 1998 ,  Spencer and MacDougall-Shackleton 2011 ). The majority of this work has focused on bird song ( Nowicki et al. 2002 ,  Buchanan et al. 2003 ,  Spencer et al. 2003 ,  Spencer and MacDougall-Shackleton 2011 ,  Schmidt et al. 2012 ), but several lines of evidence suggest that the pleiotropic effects of CORT may also be involved in the production of visual signaling systems because CORT can directly affect the expression of both melanin- and carotenoid-based traits, which are the two most common classes of pigment-based signals ( Hill and McGraw 2006 ).  Elevated CORT during development can inhibit melanogenesis in feathers ( Roulin et al. 2008 ), and darker melanin-based plumage traits can signal resistance to stress (i.e. reduced CORT secretion) in nestlings and adults ( Almasi et al. 2008 ,  2012b ,  Ducrest et al. 2008 ,  Minias et al. 2014 ). The effect of CORT on development of carotenoid-based traits is more context dependent ( Loiseau et al. 2008a ,  Cote et al. 2010 ,  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ), with evidence of both negative ( Loiseau et al. 2008a ,  Mart&iacute;nez-Padilla et al. 2013 ) and positive ( McGraw et al. 2011 ,  Lendvai et al. 2013 ,  Mart&iacute;nez-Padilla et al. 2013 ,  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ) associations between CORT and carotenoid-based signals. Importantly, both classes of pigments can be affected simultaneously. For example, administration of CORT affects both melanin- and carotenoid-based skin coloration in common lizards (  Zootoca vivipara  ;  San-Jose and Fitze 2013 ). CORT can also influence the quality of feather structure ( Romero et al. 2005 ,  DesRochers et al. 2009 ), affecting the expression of both carotenoid-pigmented ( Kennedy et al. 2013 ) and structurally colored plumage traits used for signaling adult quality ( Grindstaff et al. 2012 ,  Henderson et al. 2013 ).  The honesty of such CORT-dependent visual signals may be related to variation in immune response. Immune function is frequently correlated with degree of coloration ( Butler and McGraw 2012a ,  Kelly et al. 2012 ,  Simons et al. 2012 ), and CORT and other GCs can influence immune function and reduce resistance to disease ( Fowles et al. 1993 ,  Dhabhar et al. 1995 ,  Sapolsky et al. 2000 ,  Padgett and Glaser 2003 ,  Martin et al. 2005 ,  Ben-Nathan 2013 ). Moreover, even relatively small increases in CORT in nestlings can produce downstream effects on immune response ( Butler et al. 2010 ). This interdependency between CORT, immune function, and coloration is found in multiple contexts, with CORT mediating how parasites affect expression of carotenoid-based coloration ( Bortolotti et al. 2009 ,  Mougeot et al. 2010 ) and amount of eumelanin corresponding to immune response and activation of the HPA axis ( Saino et al. 2013 ). Indeed, these observations have led some authors to suggest that the effects of CORT on immune response could also involve effects on coloration ( Loiseau et al. 2008b ).  Although the above evidence is suggestive, our understanding of potential pleiotropic effects of CORT is limited because the CORT&ndash;immune signaling nexus is complex. Studies have addressed 1 or 2 of these factors simultaneously (e.g., environmental conditions during embryonic development can program both CORT and immune responses in ducklings;  DuRant et al. 2010 ,  2012 ), but few have integrated the relationships among CORT, coloration, and immune response and considered both short- and long-term consequences. Here, we focus on immune challenges during development as a stressor because they can have consequences for immune response in adulthood ( Butler and McGraw 2012a ,  Jenkins et al. 2013 ), and we suggest that such challenges are themselves stressors capable of activating the HPA axis. Previous work has investigated this idea in the context of infection, focusing on harmful stressors such as parasites and diseases (see above). However, factors that elicit an immune response but are otherwise not harmful offer an alternative perspective because they can provide insight into activation of the immune response without the physiological costs of coping with an ongoing infection. Immune challenges can have important consequences for the development and expression of phenotype ( Garamszegi et al. 2004 ,  Grindstaff 2008 ,  Hanssen et al. 2008 ,  Romano et al. 2011 ,  Butler et al. 2012 ), particularly traits used in signaling ( Faivre et al. 2003 ,  Alonso-Alvarez et al. 2004 ,  Peters et al. 2004 ,  Velando et al. 2014 ), and immune activation in the absence of infection can have physiological ( Ots et al. 2001 ,  H&otilde;rak et al. 2006 ,  Butler and McGraw 2012a ) and fitness costs ( Ilmonen et al. 2000 ,  Hanssen 2006 ). Yet, despite the importance of physiological context to the development of signaling phenotypes ( Vitousek et al. 2014 ), CORT levels are rarely considered in studies linking immune challenges to expression of phenotypic traits, so the role of the HPA axis in mediating such effects remains poorly understood.  We hypothesized that if noninfectious early-life immune challenges activate the HPA axis during development, (1) this could have simultaneous organizational effects on both immune function and coloration, due to the pleiotropic effects characteristic of CORT exposure; and (2) these effects occur both in the short term and during adulthood. We experimentally tested this hypothesis using captive male Mallard (  Anas platyrhynchos  ) ducklings because they develop 3 colorful patches at different times in their development: Melanin-based (i.e. pattering and black banding) and structurally based (iridescent) traits form in speculum feathers grown during development, and a carotenoid-based trait (bill color) is expressed at maturity. Using the same ducklings from a previous experiment that addressed the effect of noninfectious early-life immune challenges on immune function ( Butler and McGraw 2012a ), here we additionally consider the role of CORT and effects on plumage. Our study had 5 main predictions. (1) We expected levels of corticosterone in feathers (CORT f ), which reflect plasma CORT ( Fairhurst et al. 2013 ,  H&otilde;rak et al. 2013 ) and environmental variation experienced during early life ( Fairhurst et al. 2012a ,  2012b ,  Grava et al. 2013 ,  Harriman et al. 2014 ), to be elevated in Mallards that were given a series of immune challenges during development (see  Butler and McGraw 2012a ). Because we varied the timing of immune challenges, we further predicted that individuals receiving the challenges earliest would have the highest levels of CORT f  because the developmental consequences of a stressor (i.e. increased sensitivity and prolonged responses of the HPA axis;  Spencer et al. 2009 ) would be most pronounced in the youngest birds ( Lindstr&ouml;m 1999 ,  Dufty et al. 2002 ). Assuming that higher CORT f  reflects increased sensitivity to stress or cumulative energetic costs of responding to stressors, we expected higher CORT f  to be associated with (2) reduced melanin-based and structurally based plumage traits formed during development ( Ducrest et al. 2008 ) and (3) reduced circulating carotenoid and carotenoid-based bill color as downstream developmental consequences (&ldquo;stress hypothesis&rdquo;;  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ). Alternatively, if increased CORT f  is more closely linked to individual quality than immune-challenge treatment (&ldquo;quality hypothesis&rdquo;;  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ; also see  Legagneux et al. 2013 ,  Harms et al. 2015 ), we expected positive relationships between CORT f  and these phenotypic traits. (4) Because even small increases in CORT during early life can be detrimental to development of the immune system (e.g.,  Butler et al. 2010 ), we predicted that CORT f  would negatively covary with measures of adult immune response (i.e. at the end of the experiment). Finally, we explored the consistency of development of plumage traits and adult immune response and expected (5) that they would positively covary, as an expression of individual quality.  The specific husbandry, experimental design, and methodology of blood collection and immune-function quantification for these individuals have been described in detail elsewhere ( Butler and McGraw 2012a ); here, we provide a brief summary. We acquired 1-day-old male ducklings ( n  &equals; 48) from Metzer Farms (Gonzales, California, USA) in December 2008; they were housed together, provided food ab libitum, and randomly assigned to 1 of 4 treatment groups based on the developmental stage at which injections were administered. Individuals in experimental groups received 1 injection of nonpathogenic sheep red blood cells (SRBC) each week for 3 consecutive weeks ( Figure 1 ). Individuals in the Early group ( n  &equals; 11) received injections at 3, 4, and 5 wk old, which is the period of maximum growth. Middle-group individuals ( n  &equals; 12) received injections at 8, 9, and 10 wk old, which is when growth is complete and speculum feathers finish developing ( Drilling et al. 2002 ). Late-group individuals ( n  &equals; 12) received injections at 13, 14, and 15 wk old, which is when individuals finish molting into nuptial plumage. Control-group individuals ( n  &equals; 11) did not receive injections at any point during development (to avoid inadvertently eliciting an immune response;  Adler et al. 2001 ). Sample sizes reflect feathers available for analysis.  Timeline of immune-challenge treatment and sample collection. Individuals received immune challenges weekly for 3 weeks during either the Early, Middle, or Late treatment periods or were not challenged at all (Control). Whole blood (for determining circulating carotenoid concentration) and mass were collected prior to the Early treatment period and at the conclusion of the Adult assessment period (A). At the beginning of the Adult assessment period (B), we quantified beak coloration and circulating IgG for all individuals and initiated the PHA-induced wing-web swelling assay (additional sample collected 24 hr later), nitric oxide quantification (additional sample collected 24 hr later), and KLH-specific antibody production (additional samples collected 6 and 10 days later for primary and secondary responses, respectively). Speculum feathers used for the assessment of melanin-based patterning and corticosterone grew during the Middle period and were collected at the end of the experiment (C).  We collected ~300 &mu;L of whole blood using heparinized capillary tubes from all individuals at the beginning (week 1) and end (week 19) of the experiment by puncturing the alar vein. Whole blood was stored on ice for several hours and then centrifuged for 3 min at 10,000 rpm. We then pipetted plasma into separate microtubes for assessment of carotenoid content and stored the plasma at &minus;80&deg;C until analysis. At each time of blood collection, we also measured the body mass of each bird to the nearest gram to test whether immune challenges affected growth. To analyze plasma carotenoid content (prior to any adult immune metric assessment), we followed the hexane:methyl tert-butyl ether extraction method and high-performance liquid chromatography procedures of  McGraw et al. (2008) .  When ducks were 18 wk old, we administered a 24-hr PHA wing-web swelling test ( Smits et al. 1999 ), with wing-web thickness measured pre-challenge and 24 hr later, and also quantified nitric oxide response (a pro-oxidant that is part of the innate immune response;  Sild and H&otilde;rak 2009 ) from plasma collected at the time of both wing-web thickness measurements. Nitric oxide concentration was determined using the copper-reduction, Greiss-coloration method first described by  Sild and H&otilde;rak (2009) . Concurrently ( Figure 1 ), we also quantified circulating immunoglobulin (IgG) levels by performing an enzyme-linked immunosorbant assay (ELISA) in 96-well plates using an avian IgG-specific secondary antibody (A140-110A; Bethyl Laboratories, Montgomery, Texas, USA) that undergoes a colorimetric reaction. To further assess adult immune function, we quantified humoral immunity, or antibody production to a novel antigen, by quantifying individual humoral response to keyhole limpet hemocyanin, a nonpathogenic foreign protein. We then calculated antibody response to this specific antigen, using an ELISA similar to the circulating IgG ELISA described above, but after coating the wells with keyhole limpet hemocyanin. For specific details of these assays, please see Butler and McGraw (2012).  Ornamental beak coloration in Mallards begins to develop by 10 wk of age ( Drilling et al. 2002 ) and is completed in all birds by 16 wk (M. W. Butler personal observation; J. Metzer personal communication). When we collected blood for adult immune assessments (see above), we measured carotenoid-based beak coloration of adults using an Ocean Optics (Dunedin, Florida, USA) USB2000 spectrophotometer with a PX-2 pulsed xenon light source to measure reflectance from &lambda; &equals; 300&ndash;700 nm. We measured a 1-cm band of the right dorsolateral surface of the beak between the nares and the beak tip and binned all measurements into 1-nm increments using CLRfiles (CLR version 1.05;  Montgomerie 2008 ). We then used CLRvars in CLR to calculate the brightness, saturation, and hue scores that are, respectively, correlated negatively, negatively, and positively with carotenoid content in the Mallard beak ( Butler et al. 2012 ).  Speculum feathers, grown at 8&ndash;10 wk of age, were collected at the end of the experiment for assessment of plumage traits. We cut the fifth secondary on the left wing and placed it in a white envelope until analysis. Samples were taped to black cardstock and analyzed as in  Meadows et al. (2011)  using a USB2000 spectrophotometer and PX-2 xenon light source (Ocean Optics, Dunedin, Florida, USA) that had an independently rotating sample stage, light-source fiber-optic cable, and light-collection fiber-optic cable. The angle between the 2 fiber-optic cables was 45&deg;, and the angle of the sample was rotated until the position at which the maximal amount of light was collected (i.e. the sample was at its brightest). The angle at which the sample was positioned was recorded, and then the angle was rotated by 5&deg; away from this maximal brightness to generate a second reflectance curve. We did this because the speculum feathers are iridescent, and changes in hue occur with a change in light geometry. We repeated this process twice more at different spots on the feather, yielding 3 measurements per feather at both maximal reflectance (max) and 5&deg; off of maximal reflectance (off). Spectral curves were converted to hue, brightness, and saturation values using CLR ( Montgomerie 2008 ). Brightness, hue, and 2 metrics of saturation based on the relative reflectance in the blue (400&ndash;510 nm) and ultraviolet (300&ndash;400 nm) were all significantly repeatable ( Lessells and Boag 1987 ) within each feather (all  P  &lt; 0.0001; 0.73 &lt;  r  &lt; 0.81), so average values were used for all subsequent analyses.  We analyzed speculum feather patterns (using Adobe Photoshop CS version 5.1) from photos taken with a Nikon D70 camera under standardized lighting conditions against a gray photo board. All photos were taken with the feather in 2 different orientations to account for any differences driven by the iridescent nature of the blue component of the feather. We quantified the area of the terminal white patch on the visible side of the feather ( Figure 2 ) using the magnetic lasso tool, and measured its width along the rachis using the ruler tool. Similarly, we quantified the area and width of the black subterminal band on the other side of the feather ( Figure 2 ). Because we noticed interindividual differences in the size of the white area on either side of the rachis, we also quantified width of the white band on the side of the feather not visible when the bird is exhibiting normal feather