fficiency of the extraction by spiking 3 additional feather samples with ~5,000 cpm of  3 H-labeled CORT prior to overnight incubation and subsequent filtering (same as sample extracts). Average recovery was 85&percnt; (SD &equals; 0.4&percnt;) and, while we acknowledge that our approach of correcting by an average recovery does not account for interindividual variation in CORT f  recovery, the very low variability in our recovery samples gives us confidence that interindividual variation in recovery was minimal. Samples were analyzed in duplicate in a single assay using a commercial antiserum (product C8784, lot 081M4788; Sigma-Aldrich, St. Louis, Missouri, USA). Serial dilutions of feather extracts produced displacement curves that were parallel to the CORT standard curve. We assessed assay variability using 6 replicates of an internal standard, and the intra-assay coefficient of variation (CV) was 10&percnt;. Average detection limit (&percnt;B/B 0 ) was 17.26 pg/100 &mu;L of extract, and all samples were above this limit. CORT f  measurements were corrected for total feather length, expressed as pg CORT/mm ( Bortolotti et al. 2008 ).  To address prediction 1, we compared average CORT f  values among Early, Middle, Late, and Control treatment groups using a general linear model (GLM; SAS version 9.2). Because feathers were grown prior to administration of immune challenge in the Late group, we combined Late and Control groups in a second model, comparing CORT f  values among 3 resulting treatment groups.  To address predictions 2, 3, and 4, we used GLMs to model how the independent variables CORT f , treatment, and their interaction predicted variation in each of the plumage traits, measures of carotenoid-based traits and immune responses, and body mass and mass of testes as separate dependent variables. For analyses of plumage traits, we again used a Late/Control group because feathers were grown prior to administration of immune challenge, but 4 treatment groups (Early, Middle, Late, and Control) were used for all models of carotenoid, immune responses, mass, and testis size as these phenotypic characters were quantified at adulthood. Nonsignificant terms ( P  &gt; 0.10) were removed from final models, but CORT f  was always retained. Significant treatment effects were investigated using post hoc comparisons and assessed against Tukey-Kramer adjusted  P  values. CORT f  values were log transformed to meet assumptions of normality. Transformations applied to response variables are reported with model results. Unlike relationships with CORT, which could have direct (causal) consequences for development of immune responses, it seems very unlikely that plumage traits formed during development could themselves directly influence subsequent adult immune response. Therefore, to address prediction 5, we used Pearson correlations.  CORT f  did not differ among treatment groups, regardless of whether all groups were analyzed separately ( F  &equals; 0.99, df &equals; 3 and 42,  P  &equals; 0.41) or Late and Control groups were combined ( F  &equals; 0.72, df &equals; 2 and 43,  P  &equals; 0.49). No measure of speculum feather color (all  F  &lt; 1.04, df &equals; 1 and 44, all  P  &gt; 0.3) or patterning ( Table 2 ) was related to CORT f , and treatment did not affect any measure of feather color (all  F  &lt; 0.65, df &equals; 2 and 42, all  P  &gt; 0.5). However, Mallards that received immune challenges during the middle of development grew speculum feathers with significantly shorter, and thus smaller, black subterminal bands than birds in other groups ( Table 2  and  Figure 3 ).  Results of general linear models analyzing the relationships between the pattern of male Mallard secondary (speculum) feathers and corticosterone from the same feathers (CORT f ). See text for definitions of treatments. Significant results are in bold.  Average width of the black band on male Mallard speculum feathers in relation to when immune challenges were administered. Asterisk denotes significant difference at  P  &equals; 0.01.  Similar to when CORT f  was not an explanatory variable (Butler and McGraw 2012), treatment did not affect any measure of carotenoid beak color or levels of circulating carotenoids (all  F  &lt; 2.11, df &equals; 2 and 42, all  P  &gt; 0.11). By contrast, CORT f  was positively correlated with the level of circulating carotenoid at week 19 ( F  &equals; 6.44, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.01) and with both the absolute ( F  &equals; 7.19, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.01) and percent ( F  &equals; 6.27, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.02) increase in circulating carotenoid from week 1 to week 19 ( Figure 4 A). Additionally, CORT f  was negatively correlated with saturation of the beak color in the blue range at adulthood ( F  &equals; 4.27, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.04;  Figure 4 B). However, CORT f  was not correlated with circulating carotenoid levels during week 1 ( F  &equals; 0.49, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.49). No interaction terms between treatment and CORT f  were statistically significant for beak coloration (all  F  &lt; 2.27, df &equals; 2 and 40, all  P  &gt; 0.12) or circulating carotenoid levels (all  F  &lt; 1.02, df &equals; 3 and 38, all  P  &gt; 0.39).  Relationships between corticosterone from secondary (speculum) feathers (CORT f ; log transformed) of male Mallards and ( A ) change in circulating carotenoids from week 1 to week 19 of development (square-root transformed) and ( B ) saturation of beak color in the blue range at adulthood (square-root transformed; lower values are associated with greater carotenoid-based color). See text for definition of treatments. Feathers were grown during weeks 8&ndash;10.  Of the 5 measures of adult immune response we analyzed, only circulating IgG at week 18 showed any relationship with CORT f , but this negative trend did not reach statistical significance ( F  &equals; 3.16, df &equals; 1 and 41,  P  &equals; 0.08). Treatment significantly affected adult mass, nitric oxide response, and wing-web swelling (all  F  &gt; 2.99, df &equals; 1 and 41, all  P  &lt; 0.04), in accordance with results published previously when CORT f  was not an explanatory variable ( Butler and McGraw 2012a ). Percent mass gain during development (weeks 1&ndash;19) was also positively related to CORT f  ( F  &equals; 4.10, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &lt; 0.05;  Figure 5 ), but we found no relationship between CORT f  and body mass at week 1 ( F  &equals; 1.52, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.22), body mass at week 19 ( F  &equals; 0.28, df &equals; 1 and 41,  P  &equals; 0.6), or testis mass ( F  &equals; 0.41, df &equals; 1 and 44,  P  &equals; 0.5).  Percent gain in mass (g) from week 1 to week 19 (adulthood) in male Mallards was positively related to the corticosterone in their secondary (speculum) feathers (CORT f ). See text for definition of treatments. Feathers were grown during weeks 8&ndash;10.  Correlations between plumage phenotype and adult immune metrics revealed strong positive relationships between PHA-induced swelling of the wing-web and both the width and area of the white terminal patch ( Table 3  and  Figure 6 ). However, no relationship was detected between PHA-induced swelling and the width of the white area on the opposite (covered) side of the feather ( Table 3 ), nor was any other immune metric related to plumage traits ( Table 3 ).  Pearson correlation coefficients ( r ) and associated  P  values among measures of secondary (speculum) feather color and pattern and immune response of adult male Mallards ( n  &equals; 46, except where noted). Significant results are in bold.  Relationship between the area of the terminal white patch on the visible side of secondary (speculum) feathers from male Mallards and wing-web swelling in response to the PHA test at week 18 (adulthood). Pearson correlation:  R  &equals; 0.44,  P  &equals; 0.002. See text for definition of treatments. Feathers were grown during weeks 8&ndash;10.  Overall, there was no clear evidence of pleiotropic effects of increased CORT on immune function and coloration in Mallard ducklings as we predicted, but we did find that CORT was related to multiple phenotypic traits. We detected variation in CORT f , which indicates that the HPA axis was functional by the time the Middle treatment was administered (and feathers were grown), but this variation was apparently unrelated to the nonpathogenic immune challenge of SRBCs. Either the immune challenges did not elicit an HPA response, indicating that an immunological threshold exists for HPA activation or, more likely, the HPA response was too weak and/or brief for our feather-based measure of CORT to detect it. Variation in CORT f  is driven by strong, sustained changes in HPA activity, and both baseline levels and acute responses to stressors correlate with CORT f  ( Fairhurst et al. 2013 ), but the relative contributions of these plasma levels of CORT&mdash;and the relative influence of frequency, duration, and intensity of stressors&mdash;to the feather signal are not well understood. Thus, it is possible that our stressor was too weak to be detected using CORT f . Regardless, because treatment did not affect CORT f , a lack of relationships between CORT f  and speculum feather color or pattern, and a weak correlation with only 1 of the adult immune metrics, might be expected. If the HPA axis was not activated strongly, CORT levels would have been insufficient to cause effects on phenotype at the time of development (i.e. plumage traits) or to have had persistent developmental effects on adult immune response. Thus, our lack of relationships points to the ineffectiveness of the immune challenge to trigger a sustained elevated CORT release. This negative result is important because it suggests that repeated noninfectious immune challenges capable of shaping the development of the immune response may not be experienced by the endocrine system as strong stressors. Future studies would benefit by measuring plasma CORT measurements at the time of immune challenge to better understand how the HPA axis responds to such weak immune challenges. Moreover, assessment of the melanin content of the speculum patterning is important for understanding our results ( Field et al. 2013 ). Although traits that are predominantly eumelanin-based may be associated with CORT physiology ( Ducrest et al. 2008 ,  Jenni-Eiermann et al. 2015 ), recent studies have failed to find links between CORT levels during feather growth and pheomelanin-based feather color ( Jenkins et al. 2013 ,  Grunst et al. 2015 ). Thus, a relative abundance of pheomelanin in speculum patterning may help explain our lack of relationships but, to our knowledge, has not been assessed in speculum feathers (but see  Haase et al. 1995 ).  Despite an absence of links between CORT f  and melanin-based feather color and patterning, CORT f  was related to the developmental trajectory of the birds, and particularly to their use of carotenoids. Interestingly, this result was independent of treatment. Although we cannot assign causation to CORT, greater mass gains, within-individual increases in circulating carotenoid levels, and carotenoid-based ornament expression (see  Butler et al. 2011 ) are consistent with the quality hypothesis ( Fairhurst et al. 2014 ) and suggest that birds expressing higher baseline CORT levels benefited phenotypically. This relationship between CORT and both mass gains and carotenoid-based traits may not be surprising, given that the birds were well fed and, presumably, in good condition (see below), and such conditions are believed to be a key underpinning of CORT's positive energetic effects on growth and carotenoid expression ( Fairhurst et al. 2014 ; and see  Bonier et al. 2009 ). Yet, despite all individuals' presumed good condition and the lack of a treatment effect, CORT f  was still related to multiple traits that can reflect quality. That we found a relationship with beak color is particularly important because in male Mallards this trait signals immune function ( Butler and McGraw 2012b ) and influences female investment ( Giraudeau et al. 2011 ). Frequently, ornament expression is linked to physiological measures of individual quality by assessing immune function ( Simons et al. 2012 ), oxidative status ( Simons et al. 2012 ,  Giraudeau et al. 2013 ), or body condition ( Vergara et al. 2012 ). Our data, in conjunction with the quality hypothesis ( Fairhurst et al. 2014 ) and supported by studies in Zebra Finches (  Taeniopygia guttata  ;  McGraw et al. 2011 ) and Common Kestrels (  Falco tinnunculus  ;  Costantini et al. 2008 ), suggest that in birds that are able to cope well with energetic demands (e.g., ad libitum access to food), higher sustained levels of circulating CORT (both baseline and stress induced) may be another index of quality that is being directly signaled by enhanced carotenoid-pigmented ornamentation ( Lendvai et al. 2013 ,  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ; also see  Bortolotti et al. 2009 ,  Mougeot et al. 2010 ). However, because we found links between CORT f  and one index of quality (i.e. carotenoid-based traits) but not others (e.g., adult body mass, adult immune function), further investigation is needed to determine which types of quality-based traits are likely to be related to CORT.  Further supporting the link between CORT and carotenoid physiology, our data are based on metrics collected at 2 different time points (during development and at adulthood), and CORT deposited in feathers midway through development predicted carotenoid-based traits several months later. There are 2 likely explanations for this temporal pattern. First, HPA activity during development, as revealed by CORT f , could have had direct organizational effects on carotenoid physiology via common dietary and metabolic pathways ( Negro et al. 2001 ,  McGraw and Toomey 2010 ; also see  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ), meaning that levels of CORT during development had long-lasting effects (e.g., on assimilation or transport of carotenoids). Alternatively, baseline CORT levels may have been temporally consistent among individuals during development (e.g.,  Wada et al. 2009 ), such that early-life CORT levels were correlated with HPA activity at adulthood (also see  Ouyang et al. 2011 ). If so, variation in carotenoid-based traits at adulthood may be driven by concurrent variation in baseline CORT levels and reflected by CORT during development (i.e. CORT f ). While the effects of exogenous CORT exposure during development on later-life HPA activity have been relatively well studied ( Love and Williams 2008 ,  Spencer et al. 2009 ,  Schoech et al. 2011 ), our data suggest that natural variation (i.e. not experimentally induced) in HPA activity at multiple stages may provide insight into mechanisms driving both body growth and carotenoid-based coloration in adult animals. Although both these hypotheses are reasonable, the lack of a treatment effect on CORT f  implies that CORT did not cause the relationships with carotenoids. Instead, CORT f  could have been a proxy for an additional, unmeasured, metabolic or physiological variable that covaried with CORT (e.g., thyroid hormone;  Sharma and Chaturvedi 2009 ,  Scanes 2014 ). Future research will be necessary to elucidate the mechanism responsible for the covariation between CORT f  and phenotype that we observed.  We predicted that even small increases in CORT would result in a reduced immune function later in life ( Butler et al. 2010 ). Partially in line with this, CORT f  correlated negatively with circulating IgG levels at adulthood, but only weakly. Our prediction was based on experimental manipulations of CORT levels ( Loiseau et al. 2008a ,  2008b ,  Butler et al. 2010 ), but given the lack of a treatment effect on CORT f , it is likely that our metric of HPA activity reflected natural (i.e. unmanipulated) variation in baseline CORT levels, albeit in captive birds. Because we detected a (weak) correlation between CORT f  and only one immune metric, our data suggest that, in contrast to increases in CORT due to exogenous hormone administration or stressors, natural variation in CORT early in life may be minimally informative regarding later-life immune function. However, conditions experienced during captivity bear limited resemblance to those experienced in the wild, so this hypothesis requires testing in free-living birds.  The positive relationship between CORT f  and mass gain are in contrast to previous findings in Tree Swallows (  Tachycineta bicolor  ;  Fairhurst et al. 2013 ), but there are several distinctions between these studies. First, and most importantly,  Fairhurst et al. (2013)  used implants to experimentally elevate baseline CORT for days, whereas our immune treatment apparently did not have the same strong effects. Sustained elevated CORT levels can drive adverse phenotypic effects such as reduced mass and body size, and both these were manifest in the study by  Fairhurst et al. (2013) . By contrast, Mallards in our study with relatively high CORT apparently benefited in mass gain. Second, our study was conducted in captivity, where food was administered ad libitum and stressors were minimal, but the birds studied by  Fairhurst et al. (2013)  were wild and likely contended with an unpredictable food supply and additional stressors (e.g., weather). Third, whereas developing altricial passerine young are more susceptible to the detrimental effects of sustained, elevated CORT, precocial Mallard ducklings may have more adult-like physiology, should be more tolerant of the negative effects of CORT, and thus may be more able to take advantage of the positive energetic effects of CORT. Hence, the comparatively low levels of CORT, benign environment, and high nutritional condition experienced by developing Mallards in our study may have simultaneously influenced how CORT affected developmental mass gain and contributed to the positive CORT&ndash;carotenoid relationships we detected ( Astheimer et al. 1992 ,  Strack et al. 1995 ,  Negro et al. 2001 ,  McGraw et al. 2011 ,  Fairhurst et al. 2014 ).  Despite no known signaling function of the speculum in Mallards ( Omland 1996 ), the early-life immune challenges we administered during speculum feather growth reduced melanin-based feather patterning. The reason why this particular trait was affected, and the mechanism responsible, remains unclear. Although feather growth is costly ( Lindstr&ouml;m et al. 1993 ,  Klaassen 1995 ), and the additional demands of immune challenges during this period may have accumulated to a point that patterning was affected, birds in our study had ad libitum access to food, which suggests that they were not energy limited. Whether similar effects would be seen in wild Mallards, and the fitness implications of variation in this trait, requires additional research. We also detected a strong positive correlation between the size of the white patch on the visible, but not the hidden, side of speculum feathers and PHA-induced swelling at adulthood, evidence that this speculum trait may signal immune responsiveness. Female Mallards select males on the basis of traits other than speculum feathers ( Omland 1996 ; for a review, see  Sheppard et al. 2013 ), indicating that the speculum is not used in mate choice. However, previous work with wild and semicaptive Mallards has suggested that the speculum is correlated with condition ( Legagneux et al. 2010 ), and our work supports the possibility of the speculum acting as an honest signal. Collectively, these observed links among developmental immune challenges, melanin-based feather patterning, and adult immune response (also see  Gasparini et al. 2009 ,  Blanco and Fargallo 2013 ) suggest that it may be worthwhile to reexamine whether Mallard speculum feathers have a signaling function in contexts other than mate choice (e.g., dominance interactions;  Poisbleau et al. 2005 ,  2009 ), although more work remains to elucidate the mechanisms by which the honesty of these signals would be maintained.  In conclusion, we detected links between the HPA axis and phenotype, but these were apparently unrelated to the consequences of early-life immune challenges. This finding of a lack of pleiotropic effects of CORT on the development of plumage traits is supported by recent work ( Grunst et al. 2015 ), though our study is among the first to additionally consider immune response. Correlations between CORT f  and developmental trajectory, particularly carotenoids, indicate that these traits could be linked, but not necessarily caused, by the dietary and metabolic effects of CORT. This also highlights the importance of considering multiple physiological measures when studying the development of signaling traits. Given the low-intensity immune challenge used in our study, future work would benefit from manipulating CORT directly and/or using a stronger, extended immune challenge with an increased likelihood of simultaneously stimulating the HPA axis and influencing the development of the immune system. Although the HPA axis operates within a greater physiological regulatory network ( Cohen et al. 2012 ), the links among CORT secretion, development of the immune system, and formation of melanin- and carotenoid-based traits remain unclear. Nevertheless, our results highlight the temporal scale over which the HPA axis may operate, and reveal a novel relationship between development immune challenges and the formation of a melanin-based feather trait.  We thank M. Astor and S. Gleich for image analysis assistance, B. Bero-Buell for iridescence quantification, K. J. McGraw for input during execution of the experiment, S. and B. Butler for donating the camera, T. Marchant for allowing us to use her endocrine lab, and B. Clark and two anonymous rev